Eigenvalue Decomposition - Definitions and Facts

Prerequisites

The reader should be familiar with basic linear algebra concepts.

Competences

The reader should be able to understand and check the facts about eigenvalue decomposition.

General matrices

For more details and the proofs of the Facts below, see L. M. DeAlba, Determinants and Eigenvalues, pp. 4.1-1.15 and the references therein.

Definitions

We state the basic definitions:

Let F=R or F=C and let A∈Fn×n with elements aij∈F.

An element λ∈F is an eigenvalue of A if ∃x∈Fn, x≠0 such that

Ax=λx,

and x is an eigenvector of λ.

Characteristic polynomial of A is pA(x)=det(A−xI).

Algebraic multiplicty, α(λ), is the multiplicity of λ as a root of pA(x).

Spectrum of A, σ(A), is the multiset of all eigenvalues of A, with each eigenvalue appearing α(A) times.

Spectral radius of A is

ρ(A)=max{|λ|,λ∈σ(A)}.

Eigenspace of λ is

Eλ(A)=ker⁡(A−λI).

Geometric multiplicity of λ is

γ(λ)=dim⁡(Eλ(A)).

λ is simple if α(λ)=1.

λ is semisimple if α(λ)=γ(λ).

A is nonderogatory if γ(λ)=1 for all λ.

A is nondefective if every λ is semisimple.

A is diagonalizable if there exists nonsingular B matrix and diagonal matrix D such that A=BDB−1.

Trace of A is

tr⁡(A)=∑iaii.

Q∈Cn×n is unitary if Q∗Q=QQ∗=I, where Q∗=(Q¯)T.

Schur decomposition of A is A=QTQ∗, where Q is unitary and T is upper triangular.

A and B are similar if B=QAQ−1 for some nonsingular matrix Q.

A is normal if AA∗=A∗A.

Facts

There are many facts related to the eigenvalue problem for general matrices. We state some basic ones:

  1. λ∈σ(A)⇔pA(λ)=0.

  2. Cayley-Hamilton Theorem. pA(A)=0.

  3. A simple eigenvalue is semisimple.

  4. tr⁡(A)=∑i=1nλi.

  1. det(A)=∏i=1nλi.

  2. A is singular ⇔ det(A)=0 ⇔ 0∈σ(A).

  3. If A is triangular, σ(A)={a11,a22,…,ann}.

  4. For A∈Cn×n, λ∈σ(A) ⇔ λ¯∈σ(A∗).

  5. Corollary of the Fundamental theorem of algebra. For A∈Rn×n, λ∈σ(A) ⇔ λ¯∈σ(A).

  6. If (λ,x) is an eigenpair of a nonsingular A, then (1/λ,x) is an eigenpair of A−1.

  7. Eigenvectors corresponding to distinct eigenvalues are linearly independent.

  8. A is diagonalizable ⇔ A is nondefective ⇔ A has n linearly independent eigenvectors.

  9. Every A has Schur decomposition. Moreover, Tii=λi.

  10. If A is normal, matrix T from its Schur decomposition is normal. Consequently:

    • T is diagonal, and has eigenvalues of A on diagonal,

    • matrix Q of the Schur decomposition is the unitary matrix of eigenvectors,

    • all eigenvalues of A are semisimple and A is nondefective.

  11. If A and B are similar, σ(A)=σ(B). Consequently, tr⁡(A)=tr⁡(B) and det(A)=det(B).

  12. Eigenvalues and eigenvectors are continous and differentiable: if λ is a simple eigenvalue of A and A(ε)=A+εE for some E∈Fn×n, for small ε there exist differentiable functions λ(ε) and x(ε) such that A(ε)x(ε)=λ(ε)x(ε).

  13. Classical motivation for the eigenvalue problem is the following: consider the system of linear differential equations with constant coefficients, y˙(t)=Ay(t). If the solution is y=eλtx for some constant vector x, then

λeλtx=AeλtxorAx=λx.

Circulant matrix

For more details, see A. B&ouml;ttcher and I. Spitkovsky, Special Types of Matrices, pp. 22.1-22.20 and the references therein.

Given a0,a1,…,an−1∈C, the circulant matrix is

C(a0,a1,…,an−1)=[a0an−1an−2⋯a1a1a0an−1⋯a2a2a1a0⋯a3⋮⋮⋮⋱⋮an−1an−2an−3⋯a0].

Let a(z)=a0+a1z+a2z2+⋯+an−1zn−1 be the associated complex polynomial.

Let ωn=exp⁡(2πin). The Fourier matrix of order n is

Fn=1n[ωn(j−1)(k−1)]j,k=1n=1n[11⋯11ωnωn2⋯ωnn−11ωn2ωn4⋯ωn2(n−1)⋮⋮⋱⋮1ωnn−1ωn2(n−1)⋯ωn(n−1)(n−1)].

Fourier matrix is unitary. Fourier matrix is a Vandermonde matrix,

Fn=1nV(1,ωn,ωn2,…,ωnn−1).

Circulant matrix is normal and, thus, unitarily diagonalizable, with the eigenvalue decomposition

C(a0,a1,…,an−1)=Fn∗diag⁡[(a(1),a(ωn),a(ωn2),…,a(ωnn−1)]Fn.

We shall use the package SpecialMatrices.jl.

Hermitian and real symmetric matrices

For more details and the proofs of the Facts below, see W. Barrett, Hermitian and Positive Definite Matrices, pp. 9.1-9.13 and the references therein.

Definitions

Matrix A∈Cn×n is Hermitian or self-adjoint if A∗=A, or element-wise, a¯ij=aji. We say A∈Hn.

Matrix A∈Rn×n is symmetric if AT=A, or element-wise, aij=aji. We say A∈Sn.

Rayleigh qoutient of A∈Hn and nonzero vector x∈Cn is

RA(x)=x∗Axx∗x.

Matrices A,B∈Hn are congruent if there exists nonsingular matrix C such that B=C∗AC.

Inertia of A∈Hn is the ordered triple

in⁡(A)=(π(A),ν(A),ζ(A)),

where π(A) is the number of positive eigenvalues of A, ν(A) is the number of negative eigenvalues of A, and ζ(A) is the number of zero eigenvalues of A.

Gram matrix of a set of vectors x1,x2,…,xk∈Cn is the matrix G with entries Gij=xi∗xj.

17.2 μs

Facts

Assume A is Hermitian and x∈Cn is nonzero. Then

  1. Real symmetric matrix is Hermitian, and real Hermitian matrix is symmetric.

  2. Hermitian and real symmetric matrices are normal.

  3. A+A∗, A∗A, and AA∗ are Hermitian.

  4. If A is nonsingular, A−1 is Hermitian.

  5. Main diagonal entries of A are real.

  6. Matrix T from the Schur decomposition of A is Hermitian. Consequently:

    • T is diagonal and real, and has eigenvalues of A on diagonal,

    • matrix Q of the Schur decomposition is the unitary matrix of eigenvectors,

    • all eigenvalues of A are semisimple and A is nondefective,

    • eigenvectors corresponding to distinct eigenvalues are orthogonal.

  7. Spectral Theorem. To summarize:

    • if A∈Hn, there is a unitary matrix U and real diagonal matrix Λ such that A=UΛU∗. The diagonal entries of Λ are the eigenvalues of A, and the columns of U are the corresponding eigenvectors.

    • if A∈Sn, the same holds with orthogonal matrix U, A=UΛUT.

    • if A∈Hn with eigenpairs (λi,ui), then A=λ1u1u1∗+λ2u2u2∗+⋯+λnunun∗.

    • similarly, if A∈Sn, then A=λ1u1u1T+λ2u2u2T+⋯+λnununT.

  8. Since all eigenvalues of A are real, they can be ordered: λ1≥λ2≥⋯≥λn.

  9. Rayleigh-Ritz Theorem. It holds:

λn≤x∗Axx∗x≤λ1,λ1=maxxx∗Axx∗x=max∥x∥2=1x∗Ax,λn=minxx∗Axx∗x=min∥x∥2=1x∗Ax.

  1. Courant-Fischer Theorem. It holds:

λk=maxdim⁡(W)=kminx∈Wx∗Axx∗x=mindim⁡(W)=n−k+1maxx∈Wx∗Axx∗x.

  1. Cauchy Interlace Theorem. Let B be the principal submatrix of A obtained by deleting the i-th row and the i-th column of A. Let μ1≥μ2≥⋯≥μn−1 be the eignvalues of B. Then

λ1≥μ1≥λ2≥μ2≥λ3≥⋯≥λn−1≥μn−1≥λn.

  1. Weyl Inequalities. For A,B∈Hn, it holds:

λj+k−1(A+B)≤λj(A)+λk(B),for j+k≤n+1,λj+k−n(A+B)≥λj(A)+λk(B),for j+k≥n+1,λj(A)+λn(B)≤λj(A+B)≤λj(A)+λ1(B),for j=1,2,…,n.

  1. π(A)+ν(A)+ζ(A)=n.

  2. rank⁡(A)=π(A)+ν(A).

  3. If A is nonsingular, in⁡(A)=in⁡(A−1).

  4. If A,B∈Hn are similar, in⁡(A)=in⁡(B).

  5. Sylvester's Law of Inertia. A,B∈Hn are congruent if and only if in⁡(A)=in⁡(B).

  6. Subadditivity of Inertia. For A,B∈Hn,

π(A+B)≤π(A)+π(B),ν(A+B)≤ν(A)+ν(B).

  1. Gram matrix is Hermitian.

Positive definite matrices

These matrices are an important subset of Hermitian or real symmteric matrices.

Definitions

Matrix A∈Hn is positive definite (PD) if x∗Ax>0 for all nonzero x∈Cn.

Matrix A∈Hn is positive semidefinite (PSD) if x∗Ax≥0 for all nonzero x∈Cn.

Facts

  1. A∈Sn is PD if xTAx>0 for all nonzero x∈Rn, and is PSD if xTAx≥0 for all x∈Rn.

  1. If A,B∈PSDn, then A+B∈PSDn. If, in addition, A∈PDn, then A+B∈PDn.

  2. If A∈PDn, then tr⁡(A)>0 and det(A)>0.

  3. If A∈PSDn, then tr⁡(A)≥0 and det(A)≥0.

  4. Any principal submatrix of a PD matrix is PD. Any principal submatrix of a PSD matrix is PSD. Consequently, all minors are positive or nonnegative, respectively.

  5. A∈Hn is PD iff every leading principal minor of A is positive. A∈Hn is PSD iff every principal minor is nonnegative.

  6. For A∈PSDn, there exists unique PSD k-th root, A1/k=UΛ1/kU∗.

  7. Cholesky Factorization. A∈Hn if PD iff there is an invertible lower triangular matrix L with positive diagonal entries such that A=LL∗.

  8. Gram matrix is PSD. If the vectors are linearly independent, Gram matrix is PD.
